'''Ōhesoki no Mikoto''' (大綜麻杵命, birth and death dates unknown) was an ancient Japanese aristocrat and the ancestor of the {{ill|Mononobe no Muraji|ja|物部氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. He is also referred to as Ōsoki no Mikoto in the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft|12=draft}} and as Ōhesosoki no Mikoto in the {{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview == In the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ōhesoki is noted as the father of [[Ikashikome no Mikoto]], the mother of [[Sujin Emperor]]. While his other activities are not extensively recorded in the *Nihon Shoki*, the *Sendai Kuji Hongi*'s "Tenson Honki" section recounts that in the 8th year of Emperor Kōgen's reign, Ōhesoki was appointed as Ōne, a high-ranking ministerial position, and his brother [[Utsushikome no Mikoto]] became Ōomi (Minister). He later became Ōomi under Emperor Kaika in the 8th year of his reign.
In the {{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft|12=draft}}, he is identified as the grandfather of Tatetsukawa no Mikoto, indicating his importance in early genealogy.
Although the early genealogy of the Mononobe clan is somewhat inconsistent across historical sources, there is a general agreement that Ōhesoki was a fifth-generation descendant of {{ill|Nigihayahi no Mikoto|ja|饒速日命|12=draft|12=draft}} and a sibling to [[Utsushikome no Mikoto]]<ref>{{Cite book|author=Hoga Toshio|title=Research on Ancient Clans Vol. 8: The Mononobe Clan|publisher=Aogaki Publishing|year=2016|page=104|chapter=Four: Early Movements of the Mononobe Clan}}</ref>.
